Prince Shōtoku (聖徳太子, Shōtoku Taishi, 573–621), also known as Prince Umayado  (厩戸皇子, Umayado no ōji), was a regent and a politician of the Asuka period in Japan.
Prince Shōtoku looked to China for political and religious inspiration.
The popular name Prince Shōtoku first appeared in Kaifūsō written in 751, more than a hundred years after his death.
